post_text:
Let us #NeverForget 9/11. #PatriotDay üá∫üá∏

This photo was captured the night before. 19 years ago today, 246 people went to sleep in preparation for their morning flights; 2,997 people went to sleep in preparation for work in the morning; 343 firefighters went to sleep in preparation for their morning shift; 60 police officers went to sleep in preparation for morning patrol; 8 paramedics went to sleep in preparation for the morning shift. Not one of them lived past 10:00 AM Sept 11, 2001. We will never forget to honor you.

Life can change or be taken away from us at any moment. Remember to love a little harder, enjoy and appreciate the little things in life, and never take life for granted.

Looking for something FUN to do with the kids during this #StayAtHome time?? How about SLIME science‚ÅâÔ∏è
üëç
#TipTuesday with #OHDELA

How it Works üß™
Slime activators (borax, saline solution, or liquid starch) change the position of the molecules in the glue in a process called cross-linking! A chemical reaction occurs between the glue and the borate ions, and slime is the new substance formed.

#Science #handsonlearning

[Note: parent supervision is required. Recipe shown is not edible.]

post_text:
Dear OHDELA Community,

Last Friday US Secretary of Education Betsy DeVos noted that states will have the flexibility to cancel state testing this year given the COVID-19 situation. States choosing to do so will need to file a waiver with the US Department of Education. On Sunday, 3/22/20, Ohio Governor Mike DeWine indicated in his press conference that he would be asking the General Assembly of Ohio to suspend state testing for this year. The General Assembly will be in session this week, and it is anticipated that this legislation will be passed at that point. If passed that legislation would pave the way for the Ohio Department of Education (ODE) to submit a waiver request. OHDELA has suspended all testing planning and scheduling as we await updates on that legislation and a formal announcement from ODE. For now, all families who had scheduled a testing time in the April 3-April 17 window should assume that they will NOT test during that period. We will provide additional updates as we receive them.

~ OHDELA Administration

Dear OHDELA Community,

Last Friday US Secretary of Education Betsy DeVos noted that states will have the flexibility to cancel state testing this year given the COVID-19 situation. States choosing to do so will need to file a waiver with the US Department of Education. On Sunday, 3/22/20, Ohio Governor Mike DeWine indicated in his press conference that he would be asking the General Assembly of Ohio to suspend state testing for this year. The General Assembly will be in session this week, and it is anticipated that this legislation will be passed at that point. If passed that legislation would pave the way for the Ohio Department of Education (ODE) to submit a waiver request. OHDELA has suspended all testing planning and scheduling as we await updates on that legislation and a formal announcement from ODE. For now, all families who had scheduled a testing time in the April 3-April 17 window should assume that they will NOT test during that period. We will provide additional updates as we receive them.

~ OHDELA Administration

post_text:
Hello OHDELA community,
Today, March 23rd, through Friday, March, 27th, is spring break for OHDELA students and instructional staff. There will be no live class sessions this week. However, this is a great time to catch up on missed assignments and improve low course grades. You have access to all online courses and supplemental resources (iXL, iReady, Newsela, etc.) throughout this week. Also, if you have unsubmitted offline time from prior weeks, or if you complete offline time this week, please be sure to submit that from within the appropriate course.
Teachers are out of the office and will not be available to respond to calls or emails, but Advisors, Administrators, and Office Staff are still available via email and phone, so please reach out if you need anything. IT support will also continue to be available this week.

~ OHDELA Administration

IMPORTANT ATTENDANCE UPDATE

As we wrap up the semester and finish out our fall classes, we want to remind everyone about the offline tracker tool. To receive credit for any activities you do that are not within your class, you have to let your teachers know about them by filling out the information in the offline tracker. Examples of these sorts of activities would be studying, doing a worksheet with paper and pencil, researching another website, typing an assignment in google docs, or basically anything you do that is ‚Äúoutside‚Äù of the buttons in your classroom. Its super easy to do and the video below shows you how.

How to add time to your engagement and attendance

As we move into spring, we will be teaching you some tips on how to use this as a part of your daily school routine, but let‚Äôs use this last week of the semester to be sure everyone knows how to use this great tool to get credit for the learning being done outside the classroom!

https://youtu.be/PD1fZyOBpck

OHDELA - Using Offline Tracker
text:
IMPORTANT ATTENDANCE UPDATE

As we wrap up the semester and finish out our fall classes, we want to remind everyone about the offline tracker tool. To receive credit for any activities you do that are not within your class, you have to let your teachers know about them by filling out the information in the offline tracker. Examples of these sorts of activities would be studying, doing a worksheet with paper and pencil, researching another website, typing an assignment in google docs, or basically anything you do that is ‚Äúoutside‚Äù of the buttons in your classroom. Its super easy to do and the video below shows you how.

post_text:
Today we celebrate autumn's favorite candy, Candy Corn. Here's a brief history. The candy was invented by George Renniger of the Wunderlee Candy Company. Wunderlee was the first to sell it commercially, but the sale and production of candy corn is mostly attributed to Goelitz Confectionary Company. The Candy Corn business kept the company afloat through the Great Depression.The Goelitz Co. later changed their name to Jelly Belly, whom most of us are familiar with!

Candy Corn was first called ‚Äúchicken feed" since it resembled corn. You see Candy Corn in stores in autumn because of corn being associated with the fall harvest.

We hope you enjoy this Candy Corn treat idea for
#NationalCandyCornDay!

post_text:
"My nephew enrolled at OHDELA in 4th grade because of bullying in our public school from teachers and other students. The bullying was so intense that he would come home with a bloody nose due to his blood pressure being so high. The stress was almost more than he could bare. Now he has severe anxiety and it is very difficult for him to trust anyone. He no longer tries to talk to anyone his age because of the fear of being bullied. He has always been a good student and that is one of the many reasons he was bullied. Now that he is enrolled at OHDELA, a lot of his stress is gone due to the fact that he does not have to worry about being bullied."

~T. Morris, 2019 OHDELA Learning Coach

#bullypreventionmonth #unityday #ohdela

post_text: Let's not forget to honor #Ohio's very own John Chapman, AKA Johnny Appleseed, today! üçé
shared_text:
Ohio Channel
September 13, 2018 at 1:00 PM ¬∑

Ohio has the site of Johnny Appleseed's earliest known recorded landholdings. Appleseed (whose legal name was John Chapman) purchased two parcels on September 14, 1809: Mount Vernon town lot 147 and lot 145. Johnny Appleseed likely rested at his site on August 10, 1813, after arriving from Mansfield with alarming news of a rumored Indian attack. Appleseed returned to Mansfield with reinforcements from Mount Vernon that same day--a round trip of over fifty miles.
